summary.seg: This manuscript is an Acts and Epistles book, probably copied in the 12th century and slightly incomplete. It is a relatively high-quality production, written on good parchment and ornamented with gold. Its content is straightforward, comprising only the main text without supporting material. One unusual feature is the repetition in brief form of the heading of each book at the top of the page on which it begins.

A number of folios were replaced at the time of production, the text of the replacement leaves being copied apparently by the same scribe as the rest of the text, presumably due to some defect in the copying or damage during the production process. In some cases (pp. 33-34, 67-68) the text of these folios is indistinguishable from that of the rest of the manuscript. However, a number of replacement folios (pp. 561-562, 567-568, 575-576, 587-588) bear text in a a different ink from the rest, although the hand appears the same, suggesting that the original scribe had returned to recopy them at some later date, unless these are the work of a very skilled imitator. The reasons for these replacements must be a matter for speculation, but this could reflect an exacting level of quality control, leading to the rejection and replacement at a late stage of folios which had initially been accepted as satisfactory. A different hand has made a considerable number of corrections to the text.

The manuscript attracted considerable attention from early modern scholars of the Biblical text. In the later 17th and 18th centuries it was examined by Thomas Gale and J.J. Wetstein, and fully collated by John Mill for his edition of the New Testament, by Richard Bentley, and by John Wigley on behalf of John Jackson, for another planned edition.

support.material: Parchment (FHHF), thin and of good quality.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is paginated with the numbers [i-iii] + 1-606 + [iv-v], in brown ink, in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right, and verso, upper left. Some of these numbers have been lost due to damage.

pp. 1-30 have been paginated again with the numbers 1-30, in pencil, in Arabic numerals, recto, lower left, probably to compensate for the loss of many of the numbers of the first sequence in the early part of the manuscript.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 41 quires, of which two are quinia and the rest are quaternia.

list.item: Quire 18-1 pp. 1-14 The first folio has been lost, with loss of text.
Quire 38-2+2 pp. 31-46 The original second folio has been cancelled and replaced by another leaf, copied by the same scribe.
Quire 58-1+1 pp. 63-78 The original third folio has been cancelled and replaced by another leaf, copied by the same scribe.
Quire 88-6 pp. 111-114 The second-seventh folios have been lost, with loss of text.
Quire 138-1 pp. 179-192 The fourth folio has been lost, with loss of text.
Quire 358 pp. 529-544 The first folio (pp. 529-530) is misplaced as the seventh.
Quire 378-3+3 pp. 561-576 The original first, fourth and eighth folios have been cancelled and replaced by single leaves, copied by the same scribe in a darker ink.
Quire 388-1+1 pp. 577-592 The original sixth folio has been cancelled and replaced by another leaf, copied by the same scribe in a darker ink.
Quire 398-1 pp. 593-606 The last folio has been cancelled, without loss of text.

collation.signatures: There are quire signatures in Arabic numerals, in pencil, on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower left. They are often erroneous.

supportDesc.condition: There are losses in the margin to the fore-edge of pp. 1-30 and to the tail and fore-edge of pp. 605-606, which have been repaired with parchment patches. There are other losses due to tears to the upper outer corners of pp. pp. 115-116 and 169-170, with some loss of text and decoration. There are occasional small holes and small tears to the edge of folios (e.g. 189-190). The folios are mildly cockled and creased. There are areas of dirt, mild water staining, and mould staining (pp. 396-403). A small area of the last few folios appears slightly singed (pp. 599-606). The ink has occasionally suffered abrasion.

layoutDesc.layout:
A single column of 22 lines. 165 110
Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 32C1. Text hangs from the lines.

handNote.p: The text was copied in an upright mixed minuscule script, in brown ink, with modest variation in letter size and some flourishing of tails into the margin. There are deletions by erasure.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscription of word endings appear only at the end of lines. Breathings are both angular and round, and mute iota is usually absent but occasionally adscript. Use of the double dot is functional only. There is accentuation of all nomina sacra. Accents are sometimes joined to nomina sacra strokes. Marginal quotation marks and the double grave accent are in use.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower comma, question mark and full stop.
The same hand has added headings and other rubric in the same style in red ink.

decoDesc.decoNote: The beginning of the Epistles, on p. 169 is preceded by a pyle in red, blue, green and white paint and gold, part of which has been lost due to damage.

The text of the Epistles, on p. 169, begins with a major initial in the same style as the headpiece. The individual epistles each begin with a small ornamented initial, written in red ink and gilded (e.g. pp. 213, 477).
Sections begin with simple minor initials in red ink.
The transition between epistles on p. 234 is accompanied by line-fillers in red ink, gilded.
The beginnings of other epistles are usually preceded by vignettes in red ink, gilded (e.g. pp. 213, 232, 374, 492)

physDesc.additions:
As part of the original production of the manuscript, titles have usually been duplicated, sometimes in a more concise form, in the upper margin of the folio on which they appear.
Frequent corrections have been made by another hand in black ink, often by deleting the original text (e.g. pp. 100-101, 560). A hand using black ink has copied some initial letters (pp. 538-539).
There are occasional brief marginal notes and pen-trials in various Greek hands (e.g. pp. 1, 95, 175, 351).
Modern chapter numbers have been added in the margins, in Arabic numerals.
On f. [iii] recto-[iii] verso is an excerpt from a memorandum by John Jackson (1686-1763) Jackson, John, 1686-1763 , originally added to a copy of Mill's edition of the New Testament in Jesus College, Cambridge. This refers to information conveyed by
John Wigley Wigley, John regarding the collation of the manuscript by Mill and gives information on the contents and variant readings.
A note on f. [iii] recto by F.H.A. Scrivener Scrivener, Frederick Henry Ambrose, 1813-1891 , dated February 1855 records his collation of the manuscript. Another on f. [iii] verso refers to the misplacement of pp. 529-530.
There is a note of the former classmark F.1.13 on f. [iii] recto and a note of content on f. [iii] verso.

binding.p: 18th-century full leather binding over couched-laminate boards, with marbled pastedowns. Both boards and the spine are decorated with blind tooling. The title Acta Apostolorum et Epistulae is tooled in gold on a red patch on the spine, with the classmark on a label. There are traces of red paint on the edges, indicating that they were painted at some point.
binding.condition: The joints of both boards have begun to split, and some leather has been lost at the head and tailcaps.

physDesc.accMat: A note reading Acta et Epistolae Graece Twelfth Century MS is inserted loose at the front of the manuscript.

history.origin: The style of script indicates that the manuscript was copied in the 12th century.
